<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>
<map version="1.0.1">
  <node TEXT="Pi Architecture — Agent Loop, Tools, TUI and More">
    <node TEXT="1. Introduction — What is Pi?">
      <node TEXT="In this section"><node TEXT="Scenario: You open Pi in your terminal and type a message" /><node TEXT="Why it matters: Understanding what happens gives you power to debug, customize, and build your own agents" /><node TEXT="In summary: Why Pi is a beautifully minimalist AI coding agent and why understanding its architecture helps you build your own." /></node><node TEXT="Core Idea"><node TEXT="Pi is a minimalist AI coding agent built entirely from scratch" /><node TEXT="Two main parts: PyCore (the engine) and PyInteractive (the interface)" /></node><node TEXT="Key Concepts"><node TEXT="Pi: A minimalist AI coding agent, entirely custom-built, no external frameworks" /><node TEXT="PyCore: The agentic loop — handles conversations, tools, sessions" /><node TEXT="PyInteractive: The interface layer — TUI, CLI entry, skills, extensions" /><node TEXT="RPC Mode: Pi can also be called programmatically, not just interactively" /></node><node TEXT="SVG References"><node TEXT="PiArchitecture_AgentLoop_sketch" /></node></node>
    <node TEXT="2. The Agentic Loop — Core Engine Overview">
      <node TEXT="In this section"><node TEXT="Scenario: You ask Pi to &quot;refactor my auth module&quot;" /><node TEXT="Why it matters: Pi builds context, checks memory length, calls the LLM, reads/edits files, then replies — all via this loop" /><node TEXT="In summary: The exact sequence of steps Pi executes every time you send a message — the beating heart of any AI agent." /></node><node TEXT="Process Flow / Steps"><node TEXT="Initialize Context — assemble system prompt + skills + tools + history + your message" /><node TEXT="Transform Context — check if compaction is needed; compact if so" /><node TEXT="LLM Call — send full context to selected model" /><node TEXT="Tool Loop — model calls tools (read/edit/bash/write); results fed back; repeat until done" /><node TEXT="Final Reply — model decides no more tool calls needed; emits response to you" /></node><node TEXT="Core Idea"><node TEXT="Every message you send triggers a fixed 3-phase loop: Initialize → Transform → LLM Call" /><node TEXT="This loop is the same whether it's your first message or your hundredth" /></node><node TEXT="Key Concepts"><node TEXT="Agent Loop: The repeating cycle that processes every user message" /><node TEXT="Context Window: The combined token budget holding system prompt + history + tools" /><node TEXT="Tool Call: A structured request from the LLM to use a tool (e.g. read a file)" /><node TEXT="Turn: One complete pass through the loop, ending in a final reply" /></node><node TEXT="SVG References"><node TEXT="PiArchitecture_AgentLoop_sketch" /></node></node>
    <node TEXT="3. Context Initialization — Building the System Prompt">
      <node TEXT="In this section"><node TEXT="Scenario: You want Pi to always know your coding preferences" /><node TEXT="Why it matters: Add an agents.md file in your home or working directory — Pi loads it automatically" /><node TEXT="In summary: Exactly what gets assembled into Pi's context before every LLM call, and how to extend it yourself." /></node><node TEXT="Process Flow / Steps"><node TEXT="Load system prompt (hardcoded; override with system.md in .pi/ or --system-prompt flag)" /><node TEXT="Append agents.md files from home directory AND current working directory" /><node TEXT="Append skill descriptions (name + short description, not full skill content)" /><node TEXT="Append tool descriptions for all loaded tools" /><node TEXT="Append message history (or compacted summary if previously compacted)" /><node TEXT="Append your current message" /></node><node TEXT="Core Idea"><node TEXT="Context is built in layers: system prompt → agents.md files → skill descriptions → tool descriptions → history → your message" /><node TEXT="You can customize almost every layer" /></node><node TEXT="Key Concepts"><node TEXT="system.md: Place in .pi/ to override the default system prompt" /><node TEXT="append-system.md: Place in .pi/ to ADD to (not replace) the default prompt" /><node TEXT="agents.md: Markdown file Pi auto-loads — use for persistent project context" /><node TEXT="Skill description: Short summary loaded into context; full skill content loaded only when invoked" /></node><node TEXT="SVG References"><node TEXT="PiArchitecture_ContextInitialization_sketch" /></node></node>
    <node TEXT="4. Context Transformation — When and How Pi Compacts">
      <node TEXT="In this section"><node TEXT="Scenario: You're in a long debugging session and Pi seems slower" /><node TEXT="Why it matters: Pi may be near its context limit; compaction will summarize prior work so the session can continue" /><node TEXT="In summary: How Pi decides when to compress conversation history to stay within the model's context window." /></node><node TEXT="Process Flow / Steps"><node TEXT="Agent turn ends OR user is about to send a prompt → trigger checkCompaction" /><node TEXT="Check token count: use LLM-provided usage if available (input + output + cache read + cache write)" /><node TEXT="If no usage in response → estimate: add usage.input + usage.output + cache.read + cache.write" /><node TEXT="If total is near the context limit → run compaction summarization" /><node TEXT="Compaction = send full history to LLM with special summarization prompt → get structured summary" /><node TEXT="Replace message history with this summary for all future turns" /></node><node TEXT="Core Idea"><node TEXT="Pi calls checkCompaction at two moments: after every agent turn AND before every new prompt" /><node TEXT="Instead of estimating tokens upfront, Pi trusts the LLM's own usage numbers in its response" /></node><node TEXT="Key Concepts"><node TEXT="checkCompaction: Pi's function to decide if history needs to be compressed" /><node TEXT="Compaction trigger: After agent turn ends OR before next user prompt" /><node TEXT="Token estimation: Uses LLM response usage fields (input + output + cache)" /><node TEXT="Compacted summary: Structured checkpoint stored instead of raw message history" /></node><node TEXT="SVG References"><node TEXT="PiArchitecture_AgentLoop_sketch" /><node TEXT="PiArchitecture_CompactionSystem_sketch" /></node></node>
    <node TEXT="5. The LLM Call &amp; Tool Execution Loop">
      <node TEXT="In this section"><node TEXT="Scenario: Pi needs to refactor auth.ts" /><node TEXT="In summary: What actually happens when Pi calls the LLM — how tool calls work and how results flow back." /></node><node TEXT="Process Flow / Steps"><node TEXT="Full context (with assembled prompt + history) sent to configured LLM provider" /><node TEXT="LLM returns either: (a) tool call or (b) final text reply" /><node TEXT="If tool call: Pi executes the tool, captures output, appends to context" /><node TEXT="LLM is called again with the updated context including tool result" /><node TEXT="Steps 3-4 repeat until LLM returns a final text reply" /><node TEXT="Final reply is shown to the user; turn ends" /></node><node TEXT="Core Idea"><node TEXT="Pi sends the full assembled context to the LLM → model either makes a tool call OR gives a final reply" /><node TEXT="Tool results flow back into the LLM; this repeats until no more tool calls" /></node><node TEXT="Key Concepts"><node TEXT="Tool call: Structured JSON returned by LLM specifying which tool to invoke and with what args" /><node TEXT="Tool result: The output of executing that tool, appended back to context" /><node TEXT="Provider: Which LLM serves the call — can be OpenAI, Anthropic, Kimi, Minimax, etc." /><node TEXT="Turn: Entire tool loop from first LLM call to final reply" /></node><node TEXT="SVG References"><node TEXT="PiArchitecture_AgentLoop_sketch" /></node></node>
    <node TEXT="6. Sessions &amp; Memory — JSONL Storage">
      <node TEXT="In this section"><node TEXT="Scenario: You worked on a bug last week and want to see what Pi did" /><node TEXT="Why it matters: Navigate to the JSONL file in ~/.pi/agent/sessions — every message is there, readable in any editor" /><node TEXT="In summary: Where and how Pi stores your conversation sessions — and why JSONL is the ideal format for this." /></node><node TEXT="Process Flow / Steps"><node TEXT="Pi maps sessions to working directories (path encoded as directory name)" /><node TEXT="Each session = one .jsonl file with a unique ID" /><node TEXT="Every message (user, assistant, tool call, tool result) is appended as a new JSON line" /><node TEXT="Each line contains: id, parentId, type, role, content, timestamp" /><node TEXT="Compacted summaries replace raw history lines when compaction occurs" /></node><node TEXT="Core Idea"><node TEXT="Sessions are stored as JSONL files (one JSON object per line) organized by working directory" /><node TEXT="JSONL allows appending new messages without rewriting the entire file" /></node><node TEXT="Key Concepts"><node TEXT="JSONL: JSON Lines — one JSON object per line; easy to append without parsing the whole file" /><node TEXT="Session file: .jsonl file in ~/.pi/agent/sessions/&lt;directory&gt;/" /><node TEXT="Working directory mapping: Sessions are organized by the directory Pi was run in" /><node TEXT="Append-only: New messages are always appended to end — never overwrites old lines" /></node><node TEXT="SVG References"><node TEXT="PiArchitecture_SessionTree_sketch" /></node></node>
    <node TEXT="7. Session Tree Structure — Forking Conversations">
      <node TEXT="In this section"><node TEXT="Scenario: Pi suggested a refactor you didn't like — but you're 10 messages in" /><node TEXT="Why it matters: Use /tree to navigate back to before the suggestion and fork a new conversation from there" /><node TEXT="In summary: Why Pi sessions are a tree (not a list) and how the parentId field enables conversation forking." /></node><node TEXT="Process Flow / Steps"><node TEXT="Every message written to JSONL has an id field (unique) and a parentId (previous message's id)" /><node TEXT="Messages with the SAME parentId = forked branches from the same parent" /><node TEXT="Pi reads the tree by following parentId chains" /><node TEXT="/tree command in TUI shows all branches visually" /><node TEXT="You can select any node to jump back and fork a new branch from that point" /><node TEXT="All branches live in the same .jsonl file — nothing is deleted" /></node><node TEXT="Core Idea"><node TEXT="Every message has a parentId pointing to the message it branched from — this creates a tree automatically" /><node TEXT="You can fork at any point (/tree to navigate, select a past node, start fresh from there)" /></node><node TEXT="Key Concepts"><node TEXT="parentId: Reference to the previous message — creates the tree structure" /><node TEXT="Fork: Start a new branch from any past message; both branches coexist in the file" /><node TEXT="/tree: TUI command to visualize and navigate all conversation branches" /><node TEXT="Branch: A path through the conversation tree; multiple can stem from one parent" /></node><node TEXT="SVG References"><node TEXT="PiArchitecture_SessionTree_sketch" /></node></node>
    <node TEXT="8. Core Tools — The Minimal Toolbox">
      <node TEXT="In this section"><node TEXT="Scenario: You want Pi to refactor a function" /><node TEXT="In summary: Pi's deliberately minimal tool set — 4 core tools — and why this is enough for most coding tasks." /></node><node TEXT="Process Flow / Steps"><node TEXT="LLM decides which tool to call and with what arguments" /><node TEXT="Pi executes the tool (file I/O, shell command, etc.)" /><node TEXT="Result is returned to the LLM as a tool response" /><node TEXT="For read-only mode: run Pi with --tools read,grep,find to restrict to safe tools" /><node TEXT="Add extra tools: ask Pi to create a new tool, or install packages" /></node><node TEXT="Core Idea"><node TEXT="Pi ships with 4 tools: read, bash, edit, write" /><node TEXT="Grep and find also exist but are disabled by default (read-only mode only)" /></node><node TEXT="Key Concepts"><node TEXT="read: Read any file from the filesystem" /><node TEXT="bash: Execute arbitrary shell commands" /><node TEXT="edit: Apply targeted changes to an existing file" /><node TEXT="write: Create or overwrite a file" /><node TEXT="Read-only mode: --tools read,grep,find — useful for programmatic/RPC use" /></node><node TEXT="SVG References"><node TEXT="PiArchitecture_CoreTools_sketch" /></node></node>
    <node TEXT="9. Extensions — Extending Pi's Capabilities">
      <node TEXT="In this section"><node TEXT="Scenario: You want Pi to search the web before answering coding questions" /><node TEXT="Why it matters: Install the web-search extension — it registers a new tool and Pi can use it immediately" /><node TEXT="In summary: How Pi's extension system lets you add new tools, subscribe to events, and modify the agent without touching core code." /></node><node TEXT="Process Flow / Steps"><node TEXT="Write extension as TypeScript package" /><node TEXT="Package defines which events to subscribe to and what to do" /><node TEXT="When Pi starts, it loads all installed extensions" /><node TEXT="Extension hooks fire at the appropriate points in the agent loop" /><node TEXT="New tools registered by extensions appear in Pi's tool list" /><node TEXT="Custom commands/shortcuts available immediately in TUI" /></node><node TEXT="Core Idea"><node TEXT="Extensions are TypeScript packages that plug into Pi's event system" /><node TEXT="They can add tools, commands, keyboard shortcuts, system prompt content, and custom message rendering" /></node><node TEXT="Key Concepts"><node TEXT="Extension: A TypeScript package that plugs into Pi's event system" /><node TEXT="Event subscription: Register to fire code when specific loop events occur" /><node TEXT="Tool registration: Add entirely new tools (e.g. web search, browser, API calls)" /><node TEXT="Modular design: Pi's architecture explicitly supports this — no hacks needed" /></node></node>
    <node TEXT="10. System Prompt Deep Dive — What Pi Tells Itself">
      <node TEXT="In this section"><node TEXT="Scenario: You want Pi to always use strict TypeScript style" /><node TEXT="Why it matters: Add to append-system.md: &quot;Always use strict TypeScript. Prefer interfaces over type aliases.&quot;" /><node TEXT="In summary: What Pi's default system prompt contains and the exact mechanisms to customize it." /></node><node TEXT="Core Idea"><node TEXT="Pi's system prompt is ~20 lines — extremely minimal" /><node TEXT="It tells the agent what it is, lists skills with markup tags, and includes current date + working directory" /></node><node TEXT="Key Concepts"><node TEXT="System prompt: The root instruction set passed to the LLM at every turn" /><node TEXT="Skills markup: Skills are embedded with XML-like tags in the prompt — this allows TUI to parse them" /><node TEXT="append-system.md: Adds your content after Pi's default prompt without replacing it" /><node TEXT="system.md: Completely replaces Pi's default prompt — use with caution" /></node></node>
    <node TEXT="11. CLI Entry Point — From Command to Agent Session">
      <node TEXT="In this section"><node TEXT="Scenario: You want to call Pi from a CI pipeline non-interactively" /><node TEXT="Why it matters: Use STDIO mode — pass your prompt as argument; Pi runs, responds, exits" /><node TEXT="In summary: How typing pi in a terminal becomes a running agent session — the two files that make it work." /></node><node TEXT="Core Idea"><node TEXT="Two files handle startup: client.ts (receives the command) and main.ts (orchestrates everything)" /><node TEXT="It's not until main.ts that the actual agent session is created" /></node><node TEXT="Key Concepts"><node TEXT="client.ts: Entry point; receives command, delegates to main" /><node TEXT="main.ts: Parses args, loads config, loads extensions, creates session, runs mode" /><node TEXT="Interactive mode: Full TUI experience" /><node TEXT="RPC mode: Programmatic API calls to Pi" /><node TEXT="STDIO mode: Pass a prompt via CLI arg; Pi runs once and exits" /></node></node>
    <node TEXT="12. Terminal User Interface — The TUI Design">
      <node TEXT="In this section"><node TEXT="Scenario: You notice Pi doesn't flicker when updating output" /><node TEXT="Why it matters: The component-based rendering avoids full screen redraws — each component only updates its own region" /><node TEXT="In summary: Why Pi's TUI is notable, how it's built, and the component model that makes it fast and flicker-free." /></node><node TEXT="Core Idea"><node TEXT="Pi's TUI is completely custom — no Textual, no React Terminal, no third-party UI lib" /><node TEXT="It's component-based: each component manages its own rendering, input handling, and dynamic updates" /></node><node TEXT="Key Concepts"><node TEXT="Custom TUI: Built entirely in TypeScript for Pi — no external TUI libraries" /><node TEXT="Component-based: Each component = own render logic + input handling + dynamic updates" /><node TEXT="Event subscription: Components subscribe to agent loop events to update dynamically" /><node TEXT="No flicker: Each component redraws independently — no full screen clear/redraw" /></node></node>
    <node TEXT="13. Skills System — How Pi Reads and Uses Skills">
      <node TEXT="In this section"><node TEXT="Scenario: You invoke /skill:transcript-to-notes" /><node TEXT="Why it matters: Pi doesn't embed 500 lines of skill instructions into every prompt — it reads them only when needed, keeping context lean" /><node TEXT="In summary: The clever two-step process by which Pi makes skill descriptions available to the LLM while keeping full content lazy-loaded." /></node><node TEXT="Process Flow / Steps"><node TEXT="Skill descriptions (short) are listed in system prompt at startup" /><node TEXT="User types /skill:&lt;name&gt; in TUI" /><node TEXT="TUI intercepts the command (never reaches PyCore raw)" /><node TEXT="TUI transforms it into a structured message with: name, description, and file location" /><node TEXT="This transformed message is sent to the LLM" /><node TEXT="LLM calls read tool on the provided location to get full skill content" /><node TEXT="LLM then executes the skill's instructions" /><node TEXT="Custom /commands (not skills): TUI replaces them with full prompt text directly — never reach PyCore" /></node><node TEXT="Core Idea"><node TEXT="Skills are .md files with detailed instructions; only their description goes into the system prompt" /><node TEXT="When a skill is invoked, the TUI intercepts the command and sends the skill's location — Pi reads it on demand" /></node><node TEXT="Key Concepts"><node TEXT="Skill: A .md file with detailed instructions — only description in system prompt" /><node TEXT="Skill invocation: /skill:&lt;name&gt; — intercepted by TUI, not passed raw to PyCore" /><node TEXT="Lazy loading: Full skill content loaded by LLM on demand via read tool" /><node TEXT="Custom commands: Slash commands that are simple prompt replacements — fully expanded at TUI layer" /></node><node TEXT="SVG References"><node TEXT="PiArchitecture_SkillsSystem_sketch" /></node></node>
  </node>
</map>